WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.960 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:09.430 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:09.430 --> 00:00:11.650 align:middle line:84%
>>MICHAEL JAWER: So
way back in the 1990s,

00:00:11.650 --> 00:00:13.990 align:middle line:84%
I was working in the commercial
real estate industry.

00:00:13.990 --> 00:00:14.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH:
Well that sounds

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:16.667 align:middle line:84%
like a natural segue to the
"Sensitive Soul" author.

00:00:16.667 --> 00:00:17.467 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Sure.

00:00:17.467 --> 00:00:19.925 align:middle line:84%
A feeling went up the spine
like this is just not ordinary.

00:00:19.925 --> 00:00:21.050 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Not normal, yeah.

00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:22.330 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: But it is very human.

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:24.573 align:middle line:84%
One example might actually
be Greta Thunberg.

00:00:24.573 --> 00:00:25.990 align:middle line:84%
She went into this
depression then

00:00:25.990 --> 00:00:27.580 align:middle line:90%
she came out this crusader.

00:00:27.580 --> 00:00:29.290 align:middle line:84%
So that these kinds
of experiences,

00:00:29.290 --> 00:00:31.660 align:middle line:84%
which are traumatic,
have a resonance to them.

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:33.118 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I mean
with someone who's

00:00:33.118 --> 00:00:35.830 align:middle line:84%
five to give a 20-minute
discourse on the nature of God

00:00:35.830 --> 00:00:38.290 align:middle line:84%
and man, it would certainly
seem it's not coming

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:40.180 align:middle line:90%
from his personal experience.

00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:42.700 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: They are dissociating
from their own day-to-day

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:43.300 align:middle line:90%
experience.

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:45.133 align:middle line:84%
And the question is
what are they accessing?

00:00:45.133 --> 00:00:48.940 align:middle line:90%


00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:50.620 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Today's
guest, Michael Jawer,

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:52.660 align:middle line:84%
is saying some of us
are more thin-walled

00:00:52.660 --> 00:00:54.280 align:middle line:90%
and others more thick-walled.

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:55.550 align:middle line:90%
What does this mean?

00:00:55.550 --> 00:00:58.250 align:middle line:84%
It means that we have different
levels of sensitivity,

00:00:58.250 --> 00:01:00.130 align:middle line:84%
which has implications
for each one of us.

00:01:00.130 --> 00:01:02.170 align:middle line:84%
For example a
thin-walled person might

00:01:02.170 --> 00:01:06.040 align:middle line:84%
be overly sensitive to pretty
much everything emotionally.

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.247 align:middle line:84%
But it may be opened up on
more sublime connection levels.

00:01:09.247 --> 00:01:11.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's kind of where we're
going to go in the conversation

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:13.000 align:middle line:90%
is everywhere in between.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:14.197 align:middle line:90%
Welcome, Michael.

00:01:14.197 --> 00:01:16.030 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: It's a pleasure
to be here, Regina.

00:01:16.030 --> 00:01:17.650 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And the book's
called "Sensitive Soul."

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:18.450 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yes.

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:20.770 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: And so we're
going to spend a lot of time

00:01:20.770 --> 00:01:23.530 align:middle line:10%
on anecdotes because the
book is loaded with them

00:01:23.530 --> 00:01:25.450 align:middle line:10%
and people love anecdotes.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:27.292 align:middle line:10%
So before we go there,
let's first of all,

00:01:27.292 --> 00:01:28.750 align:middle line:10%
let everybody get
to know you a bit

00:01:28.750 --> 00:01:31.930 align:middle line:10%
and let them get to know you a
bit in terms of your background

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:35.200 align:middle line:10%
in terms of both psychological
and paranormal research,

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:36.950 align:middle line:10%
so they'll know where
you're coming from.

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:37.750 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Sure.

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:40.360 align:middle line:84%
Well I never really expected
to delve into the subject

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:42.610 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to be talking
about, but going back--

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:43.985 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well
how did it happen?

00:01:43.985 --> 00:01:47.140 align:middle line:10%
>>JAWER: So about 25 years
ago, way back in the 1990s,

00:01:47.140 --> 00:01:49.840 align:middle line:10%
I was actually working in the
commercial real estate industry

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:52.330 align:middle line:10%
representing a commercial
building owners and managers--

00:01:52.330 --> 00:01:54.288 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Well that sounds
like a natural segue

00:01:54.288 --> 00:01:56.678 align:middle line:10%
to the "Sensitive Soul" author.

00:01:56.678 --> 00:01:57.970 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Well it's interesting.

00:01:57.970 --> 00:02:00.250 align:middle line:84%
There is a straight
line going back.

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:02.440 align:middle line:10%
So I was representing
this organization

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.630 align:middle line:10%
and working with the
Environmental Protection

00:02:04.630 --> 00:02:07.120 align:middle line:10%
Agency, because there's
something called sick building

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:09.130 align:middle line:10%
syndrome that occasionally
people read about.

00:02:09.130 --> 00:02:13.240 align:middle line:84%
And it's when a building becomes
unhealthy for people to be in

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:16.120 align:middle line:84%
or, at the very least, there's
certain people in the building

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:19.120 align:middle line:84%
that don't work in the
building very well because they

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:19.960 align:middle line:90%
feel sick.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:21.460 align:middle line:84%
And then they go
out of the building

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:22.670 align:middle line:90%
and they feel much better.

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:25.240 align:middle line:84%
So the question is how do you
prevent sick building syndrome?

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:27.730 align:middle line:84%
And how do you assist
the property managers

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:32.085 align:middle line:84%
and the engineers to take care
of it if problems do arise?

00:02:32.085 --> 00:02:33.460 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
I was working on.

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.520 align:middle line:84%
And in researching this
and in developing guidance

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:39.543 align:middle line:84%
that the building owners and
managers could put to use,

00:02:39.543 --> 00:02:40.960 align:middle line:84%
I was talking to
people who'd been

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:44.680 align:middle line:84%
affected by poor indoor air
and so-called sick buildings.

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:48.580 align:middle line:84%
And some of them
related to me that they

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:51.130 align:middle line:84%
had been super
sensitive to things

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:53.230 align:middle line:84%
preceding this
particular environment

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:54.550 align:middle line:90%
situation in the building.

00:02:54.550 --> 00:02:58.570 align:middle line:84%
And some of them said they
were sensitive to electricity,

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:00.250 align:middle line:90%
to smells.

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:03.850 align:middle line:84%
And some said that they
had anomalous or paranormal

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:05.440 align:middle line:90%
sensitivities.

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:07.000 align:middle line:84%
I never thought,
Regina, that I would

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.310 align:middle line:84%
be hearing this kind of
information from folks.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:14.950 align:middle line:84%
But I'm grateful because I think
they confided in me as they

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.650 align:middle line:84%
understood that this was a
project to try to improve

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:19.660 align:middle line:90%
the environment of buildings.

00:03:19.660 --> 00:03:21.700 align:middle line:84%
And we got to
talking and I began

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:27.040 align:middle line:84%
to wonder whether
sensitivity as a phenomenon

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:29.590 align:middle line:84%
is just different
for different people.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:31.990 align:middle line:84%
That certain people
are more sensitive

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:35.380 align:middle line:84%
for various and sundry reasons
in any particular situation.

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:37.720 align:middle line:84%
And a so-called
sick building just

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:40.060 align:middle line:84%
sort of prompts them
in a particular way

00:03:40.060 --> 00:03:43.160 align:middle line:84%
and becomes a manifest
difficulty for them.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.830 align:middle line:84%
So that's really what
drew me into this.

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:49.630 align:middle line:84%
And I had a preexisting
interest in anomalous phenomena.

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:51.610 align:middle line:84%
I'd had a couple of
experiences myself.

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:53.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I want to hear about
this before we go too far.

00:03:53.350 --> 00:03:54.150 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Sure.

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:56.080 align:middle line:84%
And within my family,
there's sort of lore,

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:58.600 align:middle line:84%
especially on my mom's
side of the family,

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:00.980 align:middle line:84%
of some psychical
abilities maybe

00:04:00.980 --> 00:04:02.570 align:middle line:90%
or just incidents that happened.

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:04.720 align:middle line:84%
So I've always had kind of
a side interest in this.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:08.360 align:middle line:84%
So when folks confided
in me, I thought, well,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:09.680 align:middle line:90%
this is interesting.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:11.890 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I can explore
this a little further

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:13.100 align:middle line:90%
and see what happens.

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:16.850 align:middle line:84%
So since then, the
past 25 years or so,

00:04:16.850 --> 00:04:20.770 align:middle line:84%
I've been conducting sort of my
own independent investigation

00:04:20.770 --> 00:04:22.270 align:middle line:84%
talking to lots of
different people,

00:04:22.270 --> 00:04:26.560 align:middle line:84%
conducting a wide ranging
survey into a different forms

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:29.050 align:middle line:84%
of sensitivity, and
compiling results,

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:34.180 align:middle line:84%
and trying to be skeptical along
the way, trying to really hold

00:04:34.180 --> 00:04:36.490 align:middle line:84%
up to scrutiny what
people tell me,

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:38.560 align:middle line:84%
and try to figure
out sort of nature

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:40.812 align:middle line:84%
and nurture mix that
accounts for different types

00:04:40.812 --> 00:04:43.270 align:middle line:84%
of sensitivities, including
the extraordinary ones that are

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:45.080 align:middle line:90%
described in this latest book.

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:45.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:48.100 align:middle line:84%
And we'll get into all kinds
of possibilities there.

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.660 align:middle line:84%
It's up to each
person to see what

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:52.150 align:middle line:90%
it is they feel they relate to.

00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:54.790 align:middle line:84%
But first of all, I want to
know about your own experience,

00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:56.230 align:middle line:90%
anomalous experiences.

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:57.280 align:middle line:90%
What happened?

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:01.450 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well a couple of really
interesting situations, really

00:05:01.450 --> 00:05:02.320 align:middle line:90%
out of left field.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:06.430 align:middle line:84%
And I can't say that it's a
recurring theme in my life,

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:08.260 align:middle line:84%
but just happened
a couple of times

00:05:08.260 --> 00:05:09.710 align:middle line:90%
and gets you to wondering.

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:13.120 align:middle line:84%
So one example is
after my grandfather

00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:16.120 align:middle line:84%
died, my mom's father, we
had a family gathering.

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:17.955 align:middle line:84%
It was Thanksgiving
or Passover, I

00:05:17.955 --> 00:05:19.330 align:middle line:84%
don't remember
quite which but it

00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:22.180 align:middle line:84%
was within a few
months of his passing.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.540 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of the
meal, we were remembering

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:28.900 align:middle line:84%
people, specifically him, who
weren't at the table that year,

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:31.730 align:middle line:84%
who had obviously joined
us all previous years.

00:05:31.730 --> 00:05:34.870 align:middle line:84%
And within a few seconds
of mentioning his name,

00:05:34.870 --> 00:05:39.130 align:middle line:84%
there was a knocking
from the wall, maybe

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:42.910 align:middle line:84%
about six or eight feet away
from where I was sitting.

00:05:42.910 --> 00:05:44.660 align:middle line:84%
And everyone was sitting
around the table.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:46.077 align:middle line:84%
The only person
who wasn't sitting

00:05:46.077 --> 00:05:47.690 align:middle line:84%
around the table
at that moment was

00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:49.560 align:middle line:90%
my mom who was in the kitchen.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:50.990 align:middle line:90%
So it was anomalous.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:52.160 align:middle line:90%
It just came out of nowhere.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.340 align:middle line:84%
And I remember my cousin
at the time saying,

00:05:55.340 --> 00:05:59.150 align:middle line:84%
after a few seconds of complete
silence, he said, "Wooo."

00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:01.740 align:middle line:84%
And that's basically what you
say in a situation like that.

00:06:01.740 --> 00:06:02.540 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:04.165 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: But that
kind of stuck with me

00:06:04.165 --> 00:06:06.080 align:middle line:90%
because it was just so odd.

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:09.620 align:middle line:84%
Another example is a number of
years later, I'm in my mid 20s

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:13.400 align:middle line:84%
at this point, I was
living on my "bachelor

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:18.620 align:middle line:84%
pad" in suburban D.C.
and my cat was with me.

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.360 align:middle line:90%
We were close companions.

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:21.860 align:middle line:90%
His name was Dalton.

00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And I regarded him as the
George Clooney of cats,

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:26.550 align:middle line:84%
because he was just
dashing, and debonair,

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:27.800 align:middle line:90%
and handsome, and intelligent.

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:31.580 align:middle line:84%
And he wasn't scared
at all of anything.

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:34.100 align:middle line:84%
One evening, I think it was
a Saturday or Sunday night,

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:38.020 align:middle line:84%
about 1 o'clock in the morning,
I was just listening to--

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:39.770 align:middle line:84%
I think I was just
listening to the radio.

00:06:39.770 --> 00:06:43.610 align:middle line:84%
And Dalton was on the bed and
dashed under the bed, which

00:06:43.610 --> 00:06:44.900 align:middle line:90%
he never did.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:45.950 align:middle line:90%
Never.

00:06:45.950 --> 00:06:48.350 align:middle line:84%
And moments after he
dashed under the bed--

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:49.430 align:middle line:90%
I thought that was odd--

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:53.990 align:middle line:84%
I felt what I can only
describe as a presence,

00:06:53.990 --> 00:06:57.440 align:middle line:84%
again, a few feet away from
me at the foot of the bed.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.168 align:middle line:90%
And it was palpable.

00:06:59.168 --> 00:07:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't know
what to make of it.

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:02.090 align:middle line:90%
It felt uncomfortable.

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:04.340 align:middle line:84%
I decided to ease
the discomfort.

00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:06.620 align:middle line:84%
I would put my Walkman on
and listen to some music

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:09.693 align:middle line:84%
and sing along with it
and that calmed me down.

00:07:09.693 --> 00:07:11.360 align:middle line:84%
I looked at the clock,
wondered how long

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:12.590 align:middle line:90%
is this going to continue.

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:17.240 align:middle line:84%
At about 1:30, I noticed
that presence had dissipated.

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:20.520 align:middle line:90%
The feeling was no longer there.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:22.340 align:middle line:84%
Out comes Dalton
from under the bed.

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:23.480 align:middle line:90%
That never happened.

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:25.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Did you
have any sense of who

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:26.927 align:middle line:90%
the being might have been?

00:07:26.927 --> 00:07:28.760 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: I don't know
if it's a who or what.

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:29.593 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Or a what.

00:07:29.593 --> 00:07:31.470 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: I had no,
no, sense other than--

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:32.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Some presence.

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:35.150 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: It was something
that almost felt palpable.

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:38.930 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So where do you
fall on the sensitivity scale?

00:07:38.930 --> 00:07:41.360 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to talk about
a little self-test in a bit

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:43.220 align:middle line:84%
that people can
take to kind of see

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:44.480 align:middle line:90%
where they fall on your scale.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:45.485 align:middle line:84%
So where do you
fall on that scale?

00:07:45.485 --> 00:07:47.818 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: I'm actually on the
thick side of the spectrum.

00:07:47.818 --> 00:07:51.170 align:middle line:84%
As my wife can tell you,
I'm fairly thick at times.

00:07:51.170 --> 00:07:53.210 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And yet you
are sensitive enough

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:56.450 align:middle line:84%
that you could feel
this kind of presence.

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:59.540 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Yes, that seems to
be an aspect of sensitivity.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:01.150 align:middle line:90%
And I can say that the--

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:03.638 align:middle line:84%
we'll talk more about
the boundary concept

00:08:03.638 --> 00:08:05.930 align:middle line:84%
of thick and thin boundaries,
but the guy who developed

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:08.000 align:middle line:84%
it, Ernest Hartmann,
the late Ernest Hartmann

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.352 align:middle line:90%
from Tufts University.

00:08:10.352 --> 00:08:11.810 align:middle line:84%
The original boundary
questionnaire

00:08:11.810 --> 00:08:16.260 align:middle line:84%
actually has 145 questions and
12 subscales or categories.

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:17.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:08:17.060 --> 00:08:18.170 align:middle line:90%
Yours is much shorter.

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:21.110 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Unusual experiences
is one of those 12 categories.

00:08:21.110 --> 00:08:25.610 align:middle line:84%
So it's possible to be
overall thick or overall thin

00:08:25.610 --> 00:08:28.085 align:middle line:84%
but scored differently
in the subcategories.

00:08:28.085 --> 00:08:29.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That makes sense.

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:29.750 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: I'm probably--

00:08:29.750 --> 00:08:31.280 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I would
have found that, too--

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:33.140 align:middle line:84%
because my husband and
I both took the test.

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:35.659 align:middle line:84%
And we were both kind of
surprised at the results

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:38.117 align:middle line:84%
and realized those subcategories
probably would explain it.

00:08:38.117 --> 00:08:38.917 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:38.917 --> 00:08:40.850 align:middle line:84%
Let's go into what
the boundaries are

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:43.860 align:middle line:84%
and what thin wall and
thick wall constitute.

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:44.660 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yeah.

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:47.810 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that
everyone is somewhere along

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:49.910 align:middle line:84%
the spectrum from
extremely thick boundary

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:52.100 align:middle line:90%
to extremely thin boundary.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:53.660 align:middle line:84%
An extremely thick
boundary person

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:57.080 align:middle line:84%
is someone who is sort
of stoic, doesn't really

00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:00.710 align:middle line:84%
understand what they're
feeling at any given moment.

00:09:00.710 --> 00:09:03.305 align:middle line:84%
Dreams in black and white,
has sort of pedestrian dreams.

00:09:03.305 --> 00:09:05.930 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't really give a whole lot
of credence to what they dream.

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:07.520 align:middle line:90%
It's not a big deal for them.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:11.030 align:middle line:84%
Is highly organized,
kind of disciplined,

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:13.610 align:middle line:84%
sees the world in
black and white.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:16.120 align:middle line:84%
Whereas a highly thin
boundary person is precisely

00:09:16.120 --> 00:09:16.920 align:middle line:90%
the opposite.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:19.430 align:middle line:84%
They see all kinds
of shades of gray.

00:09:19.430 --> 00:09:21.620 align:middle line:90%
They're very reactive.

00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:23.270 align:middle line:84%
They're very concerned
about emotion.

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:25.520 align:middle line:90%
They react viscerally to things.

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:27.770 align:middle line:84%
Stuff that happened to
them a long time ago,

00:09:27.770 --> 00:09:30.590 align:middle line:84%
it's almost still in the
present day for them.

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:32.540 align:middle line:84%
They can recollect
things very clearly.

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:36.170 align:middle line:84%
And they also have very
colorful memorable dreams.

00:09:36.170 --> 00:09:38.960 align:middle line:84%
And then there's everybody,
all grades in between.

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:41.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's just an interesting
way to look at people.

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:43.520 align:middle line:84%
And my particular
interest, Regina,

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:46.460 align:middle line:84%
is really how it
relates to feelings

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:51.050 align:middle line:84%
and how closely identified
people are with their feelings.

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:53.600 align:middle line:84%
Because I think that's a
kind of overlooked aspect

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:56.660 align:middle line:84%
and a very fundamental aspect of
how we operate as human beings.

00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:59.210 align:middle line:84%
People don't all
operate the same way,

00:09:59.210 --> 00:10:03.300 align:middle line:84%
and feelings have a strong,
definite power to them.

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:04.790 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
also lends itself

00:10:04.790 --> 00:10:07.590 align:middle line:84%
to studying some of these
anomalous circumstances.

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:08.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:10.280 align:middle line:84%
So now this gets into
a question that's

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:12.170 align:middle line:90%
one of my favorite topics.

00:10:12.170 --> 00:10:13.700 align:middle line:84%
And that is kind
of breaking down

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:16.340 align:middle line:84%
the difference between
emotions and feelings,

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:19.580 align:middle line:84%
because oftentimes they're
perceived quite differently.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.390 align:middle line:84%
For myself, I'll just say
I've always perceived feelings

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:25.040 align:middle line:90%
as something that inform.

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:28.280 align:middle line:84%
It's more of some information
coming in that you

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:30.920 align:middle line:90%
can choose to react to or not.

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:32.120 align:middle line:90%
But it's information.

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:34.730 align:middle line:84%
It's informing, where
it seems that emotions

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:37.970 align:middle line:90%
are often reactive, reactive.

00:10:37.970 --> 00:10:40.830 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm going to give
you a little example

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:42.907 align:middle line:84%
so you can tell me
what would be going on,

00:10:42.907 --> 00:10:44.990 align:middle line:84%
because we're talking about
the sensitivity thing.

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:47.930 align:middle line:84%
And as you were talking, this
memory popped back to mind.

00:10:47.930 --> 00:10:50.930 align:middle line:84%
So my son who was
quite sensitive--

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:53.900 align:middle line:84%
and I'm pretty sensitive
so it would seem--

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:55.460 align:middle line:84%
went to a friend's
house for dinner.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:10:56.480 align:middle line:90%
And he comes up.

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:57.500 align:middle line:90%
And he's 12 years old.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.857 align:middle line:84%
He's kind of tugging
to get my attention,

00:10:59.857 --> 00:11:01.190 align:middle line:90%
because he's doing his homework.

00:11:01.190 --> 00:11:04.160 align:middle line:84%
And it's actually a
ladies dinner, right?

00:11:04.160 --> 00:11:06.710 align:middle line:84%
And he said, mom, can
we get out of here?

00:11:06.710 --> 00:11:08.090 align:middle line:90%
And I said, what's up, honey?

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:11.180 align:middle line:84%
And he said, look at
the color of the walls.

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:13.040 align:middle line:90%
I said, I know, it's awful.

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:14.090 align:middle line:90%
It's really hard.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:17.010 align:middle line:84%
And I understood
exactly what he meant.

00:11:17.010 --> 00:11:18.680 align:middle line:84%
And both of us
have a sensitivity

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:21.770 align:middle line:84%
going into people's
spaces, because oftentimes

00:11:21.770 --> 00:11:24.950 align:middle line:84%
the light, and the colors,
and the way the lighting is

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:28.050 align:middle line:84%
and all that are just
really harsh or not right.

00:11:28.050 --> 00:11:29.510 align:middle line:90%
Something's off in them.

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:33.710 align:middle line:84%
So that's a feeling it seems,
although his response became

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:34.750 align:middle line:90%
emotional.

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:35.750 align:middle line:90%
You see what I'm saying?

00:11:35.750 --> 00:11:36.950 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yes, yes.

00:11:36.950 --> 00:11:40.220 align:middle line:84%
And I should say that
what you're describing

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:42.470 align:middle line:84%
was summed up by
a series of books

00:11:42.470 --> 00:11:44.460 align:middle line:84%
actually by a woman
named Elaine Aron.

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:45.507 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh.

00:11:45.507 --> 00:11:47.090 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: "The Highly
Sensitive Person"

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:51.200 align:middle line:84%
is the name of her series
of books and website.

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:54.140 align:middle line:84%
And that's where I learned a
lot about different aspects

00:11:54.140 --> 00:11:55.460 align:middle line:90%
of being highly sensitive.

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:56.900 align:middle line:90%
She's out in the West Coast.

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:59.760 align:middle line:84%
And so what you're describing
is fairly typical for highly

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:00.560 align:middle line:90%
sensitive people.

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:02.768 align:middle line:84%
They react to all kinds of
things in the environment.

00:12:02.768 --> 00:12:03.680 align:middle line:90%
So you're right.

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:06.110 align:middle line:90%
The feeling is a reaction.

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:08.550 align:middle line:84%
Now people define feelings
and emotions differently.

00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:10.280 align:middle line:84%
There are neuroscientists
who describe it

00:12:10.280 --> 00:12:12.590 align:middle line:84%
in very different
ways than I would.

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:14.472 align:middle line:84%
But I agree with
you that the feeling

00:12:14.472 --> 00:12:15.680 align:middle line:90%
is something that's internal.

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:17.540 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, it's kind
of information coming in.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:18.650 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Correct, correct.

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:20.232 align:middle line:84%
And it's an assessment,
really, of--

00:12:20.232 --> 00:12:21.815 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: An assessment,
that's right.

00:12:21.815 --> 00:12:22.910 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: --how you're
feeling, how you're doing

00:12:22.910 --> 00:12:24.270 align:middle line:90%
in that particular situation.

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:26.840 align:middle line:84%
So feelings are
essential to being human.

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:30.868 align:middle line:84%
If we weren't feeling creatures,
we would be zombies or robots,

00:12:30.868 --> 00:12:31.910 align:middle line:90%
and that would be no fun.

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:32.710 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:35.990 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: The emotions, as
the word suggests, to emote

00:12:35.990 --> 00:12:38.750 align:middle line:90%
is to express a feeling.

00:12:38.750 --> 00:12:41.880 align:middle line:84%
And people differ in that
way along that scale.

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:45.620 align:middle line:84%
Also some people are much
more emotive and some less so.

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.110 align:middle line:84%
And again, the thick to
thin boundary spectrum

00:12:48.110 --> 00:12:50.780 align:middle line:84%
gets to that aspect of
people's reactivity.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:54.500 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So would people
who are, say, more sensitive

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:55.640 align:middle line:90%
be more reactive?

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:57.080 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yes, very much so.

00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:57.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:12:57.890 --> 00:12:59.480 align:middle line:84%
Even if they don't express
it, because you have

00:12:59.480 --> 00:13:02.130 align:middle line:84%
extroverts and introverts, and
you get into that whole thing.

00:13:02.130 --> 00:13:04.213 align:middle line:84%
So they may not express
it, but they're definitely

00:13:04.213 --> 00:13:05.060 align:middle line:90%
reacting to it.

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:05.960 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: That's
absolutely right.

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:06.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:08.720 align:middle line:84%
So I think who you're
talking to right now,

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:12.470 align:middle line:84%
our audience is probably going
to be very much thin-walled

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:15.187 align:middle line:90%
dominant, just so you know.

00:13:15.187 --> 00:13:17.770 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well that's a big part
of my audience over the years,

00:13:17.770 --> 00:13:18.040 align:middle line:90%
sure.

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:19.415 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's
what I'm saying.

00:13:19.415 --> 00:13:21.385 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I think you've
got your audience here.

00:13:21.385 --> 00:13:21.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:21.550 --> 00:13:23.350 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about the
notion, because we

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:25.690 align:middle line:84%
want to segue into
the notion of some

00:13:25.690 --> 00:13:28.060 align:middle line:84%
of these anomalous or
paranormal experiences.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:30.640 align:middle line:84%
And you say that exceptional
abilities in humans

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:33.970 align:middle line:84%
are more a matter of extended
and connected empathy

00:13:33.970 --> 00:13:36.760 align:middle line:84%
rather than, say, what
we know as telepathy.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:39.088 align:middle line:90%
Tell us what that means.

00:13:39.088 --> 00:13:40.880 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well we're
empathizing or we ought

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:42.900 align:middle line:90%
to be all the time with people.

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:45.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean that's what makes
the world go around.

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:50.090 align:middle line:84%
What I sort of set out in this
latest book "Sensitive Soul" is

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:53.060 align:middle line:84%
that there's a variety of
conditions and capabilities

00:13:53.060 --> 00:13:56.180 align:middle line:84%
that people have that are
conditioned to a greater

00:13:56.180 --> 00:13:57.830 align:middle line:84%
extent, influenced
to a greater extent,

00:13:57.830 --> 00:14:01.460 align:middle line:84%
by their mode of feeling,
by the way that they feel

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:04.340 align:middle line:84%
and their preponderance
to express themselves,

00:14:04.340 --> 00:14:07.280 align:middle line:84%
and the combination of nature
and nurture that sort of

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:08.850 align:middle line:90%
makes them that way.

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:14.900 align:middle line:84%
So I look at conditions
like autism, synesthesia,

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:18.110 align:middle line:84%
which is overlapping
senses like feeling a shape

00:14:18.110 --> 00:14:20.300 align:middle line:90%
or tasting a color.

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:23.838 align:middle line:84%
People think this is kind
of crazy, but it's a thing.

00:14:23.838 --> 00:14:25.130 align:middle line:90%
Some people are wired that way.

00:14:25.130 --> 00:14:26.547 align:middle line:84%
They come into the
world that way.

00:14:26.547 --> 00:14:27.518 align:middle line:90%
It's--

00:14:27.518 --> 00:14:29.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Like a
crossover of senses.

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:30.268 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Crossover of senses.

00:14:30.268 --> 00:14:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And for some people, it's
just the way they are.

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:34.303 align:middle line:84%
And they think that's
the way everybody

00:14:34.303 --> 00:14:35.720 align:middle line:84%
is until they get
to a certain age

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:37.220 align:middle line:84%
and realize they're
in the minority.

00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:41.060 align:middle line:84%
Savontism, which is having
a particular amazing skill

00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:43.550 align:middle line:84%
but having some particular
limitations mentally

00:14:43.550 --> 00:14:44.820 align:middle line:90%
and emotionally as well.

00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:48.230 align:middle line:84%
These are all examples
of people who have

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:50.300 align:middle line:90%
unique emotional processing.

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:52.790 align:middle line:84%
But interestingly, I
should mention, Regina,

00:14:52.790 --> 00:14:55.130 align:middle line:84%
that thick boundary
people have a role

00:14:55.130 --> 00:14:57.745 align:middle line:90%
in anomalous occurrences also.

00:14:57.745 --> 00:14:59.870 align:middle line:84%
They might actually be more
responsible for getting

00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:02.328 align:middle line:84%
them started, whereas it's the
thin boundary people who are

00:15:02.328 --> 00:15:03.610 align:middle line:90%
more likely to apprehend them.

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:03.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:05.000 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: It's my
suspicion anyway.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:06.458 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah,
that's interesting.

00:15:06.458 --> 00:15:08.960 align:middle line:84%
Givers, receivers, same
thing when you're even

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:11.240 align:middle line:84%
talking more kind
of telepathically

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:13.580 align:middle line:84%
of people who can
receive easier and others

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:17.850 align:middle line:84%
who can send out an
impression more successfully.

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:20.600 align:middle line:84%
So we need to first take a
look at the role of trauma

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:21.537 align:middle line:90%
in all of it.

00:15:21.537 --> 00:15:23.120 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at how
trauma plays a role.

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:24.662 align:middle line:84%
Because there was
one thing you wrote

00:15:24.662 --> 00:15:27.440 align:middle line:84%
in your book that was
interesting about a soldier

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:30.590 align:middle line:84%
that you are saying that
how a soldier reacts

00:15:30.590 --> 00:15:33.920 align:middle line:84%
in the field, which is under
extreme pressure, may be more

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:37.130 align:middle line:84%
a result of childhood
trauma than what's actually

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:38.340 align:middle line:90%
occurring in the moment.

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:42.280 align:middle line:84%
So just as an example, give
us an idea of what that means.

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:43.750 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well I
guess I would first

00:15:43.750 --> 00:15:47.920 align:middle line:84%
say that it might be helpful
for folks to picture feelings

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:49.930 align:middle line:90%
as like water.

00:15:49.930 --> 00:15:52.030 align:middle line:84%
The feelings have
an energy to them.

00:15:52.030 --> 00:15:54.970 align:middle line:84%
And we get a sense for
that by the word "emotion."

00:15:54.970 --> 00:15:58.210 align:middle line:84%
When you emote, you have a sense
of feelings flowing outward,

00:15:58.210 --> 00:16:00.340 align:middle line:90%
or you should.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:02.405 align:middle line:90%
And people differ day to day.

00:16:02.405 --> 00:16:04.030 align:middle line:84%
You could be having
a great day and say

00:16:04.030 --> 00:16:06.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm really feeling up today.

00:16:06.130 --> 00:16:10.870 align:middle line:84%
And you can just feel
happier and more expansive.

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:13.060 align:middle line:84%
Whereas other days,
you feel down.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:14.477 align:middle line:84%
And you sort of
feel constricted.

00:16:14.477 --> 00:16:15.310 align:middle line:90%
I'm just down today.

00:16:15.310 --> 00:16:18.020 align:middle line:84%
I don't know and in the
doldrums, that kind of thing.

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:20.430 align:middle line:84%
So feelings really have an
impetus or an energy to them.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:22.240 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
important to note,

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:24.520 align:middle line:84%
because in traumatic
situations--

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:26.440 align:middle line:84%
and highly sensitive
people are probably

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:30.825 align:middle line:84%
more likely to react and feel
that something is traumatic

00:16:30.825 --> 00:16:32.200 align:middle line:84%
or it becomes
traumatic for them,

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:33.820 align:middle line:90%
because they're more reactive.

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:36.670 align:middle line:84%
But the key to
weathering trauma is

00:16:36.670 --> 00:16:38.740 align:middle line:84%
to identifying what's
going on and then

00:16:38.740 --> 00:16:43.240 align:middle line:84%
being able, ultimately, to emote
and to reconcile the situation

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:45.530 align:middle line:90%
and your reaction to it.

00:16:45.530 --> 00:16:49.270 align:middle line:84%
The difficulty is that, for some
people, it can be overwhelming.

00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:52.840 align:middle line:84%
And based on where they are
on the boundary spectrum,

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:54.710 align:middle line:84%
it may prove to be
a problem later on.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:56.140 align:middle line:84%
And I guess the
perfect example is

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:59.020 align:middle line:84%
PTSD, which is one
of the conditions

00:16:59.020 --> 00:17:00.880 align:middle line:90%
that I address in the book.

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:03.700 align:middle line:84%
Most people think
of PTSD as being

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:06.190 align:middle line:90%
sort of a flashbulb memory.

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:10.180 align:middle line:84%
People have an immediate
reaction when a car backfires,

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:15.670 align:middle line:84%
and they're back on the
battlefield in Iraq, let's say.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:19.640 align:middle line:84%
And they're flooded by the sense
that they had at that moment.

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:22.700 align:middle line:84%
So that's the popular
conception of PTSD.

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:25.359 align:middle line:84%
And it tends to be that
way for most people

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:26.920 align:middle line:90%
that suffer from PTSD.

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:32.020 align:middle line:84%
But anywhere from 15%-30% of
folks who suffer from PTSD

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:33.710 align:middle line:90%
experience it differently.

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:38.180 align:middle line:84%
So that there is
a prompt, but they

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:41.450 align:middle line:84%
don't get the immediate
visceral reaction of it.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:45.470 align:middle line:84%
Their form is more
dissociated form of PTSD.

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:48.230 align:middle line:84%
In other words, they're not
feeling their feelings so much.

00:17:48.230 --> 00:17:51.305 align:middle line:84%
And they're just sort of
depressed and not sure.

00:17:51.305 --> 00:17:52.680 align:middle line:84%
They're walking
through pea soup.

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:55.850 align:middle line:84%
They just don't know
really what's the matter.

00:17:55.850 --> 00:17:58.010 align:middle line:84%
So it really speaks to the
way the trauma plays out

00:17:58.010 --> 00:17:59.390 align:middle line:90%
with different people.

00:17:59.390 --> 00:18:01.070 align:middle line:84%
And people's
predilection for trauma,

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:04.100 align:middle line:84%
obviously, has something to do
with their innate sensitivity

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:08.108 align:middle line:84%
at the time that occurrence
happens, to what extent

00:18:08.108 --> 00:18:09.650 align:middle line:84%
they're overwhelmed
or to what extent

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:12.170 align:middle line:84%
they're able to fathom
what's happening

00:18:12.170 --> 00:18:14.445 align:middle line:90%
and to react to it productively.

00:18:14.445 --> 00:18:16.070 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And it
seems like what you're

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:18.500 align:middle line:84%
saying in the book
is that trauma often

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:22.040 align:middle line:84%
is at the base of people
who are displaying

00:18:22.040 --> 00:18:25.190 align:middle line:90%
exceptional abilities.

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:26.288 align:middle line:90%
Did I misread that?

00:18:26.288 --> 00:18:27.830 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well I
guess what I'm saying

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:32.510 align:middle line:84%
is that dissociation, which
is sort of part and parcel

00:18:32.510 --> 00:18:35.030 align:middle line:84%
with trauma,
dissociation plays a role

00:18:35.030 --> 00:18:37.820 align:middle line:84%
in a lot of these kinds
of anomalous phenomena,

00:18:37.820 --> 00:18:40.680 align:middle line:84%
because the feelings
sort of go Underground

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:41.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I see.

00:18:41.480 --> 00:18:43.850 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: But my perspective
on it is that the people--

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:47.420 align:middle line:84%
you wouldn't have anomalous
occurrences without people.

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:49.970 align:middle line:84%
And you wouldn't have
them without feelings

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:53.270 align:middle line:84%
that have basically
gone underground,

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:56.090 align:middle line:90%
like that kind of PTSD.

00:18:56.090 --> 00:19:00.170 align:middle line:84%
And those are the
feelings that somehow

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:02.570 align:middle line:84%
get extended into the
environment and in a sense

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:04.470 align:middle line:90%
take on a life of their own.

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:05.700 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I'm going to
throw this quote out there,

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:06.750 align:middle line:84%
and then we're
going to start going

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:08.010 align:middle line:90%
into some of these incidences.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:10.468 align:middle line:84%
Just because I love the quote
and it's in your book, right?

00:19:10.468 --> 00:19:12.720 align:middle line:84%
OK, because we're
all thinking, oh, I'm

00:19:12.720 --> 00:19:15.640 align:middle line:84%
thicker or thinner skinned than
this person or that, whatnot.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:18.510 align:middle line:84%
And then when you consider
this quote in terms of what's

00:19:18.510 --> 00:19:20.050 align:middle line:90%
normal, we're all thick.

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:20.850 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:20.850 --> 00:19:22.305 align:middle line:90%
And this is from Douglas Adams.

00:19:22.305 --> 00:19:24.930 align:middle line:84%
He says, "The fact that we live
at the bottom of a deep gravity

00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:27.330 align:middle line:84%
well on the surface of
a gas covered planet

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:31.740 align:middle line:84%
going around a nuclear
fireball 90 million miles away

00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:33.810 align:middle line:84%
and think this is
normal is obviously

00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:36.870 align:middle line:84%
some indication of how skewed
our perspective of normal

00:19:36.870 --> 00:19:37.860 align:middle line:90%
tends to be."

00:19:37.860 --> 00:19:41.350 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHING] So what
is normal anyway

00:19:41.350 --> 00:19:45.040 align:middle line:84%
that we're even surviving
here in this environment.

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:47.753 align:middle line:90%
So let's go ahead and look at--

00:19:47.753 --> 00:19:49.170 align:middle line:84%
I didn't see his
name in the book.

00:19:49.170 --> 00:19:51.540 align:middle line:84%
It was the son of the
psychologist Joseph Pearce,

00:19:51.540 --> 00:19:54.540 align:middle line:84%
what happened to him at
five when he launched

00:19:54.540 --> 00:19:56.500 align:middle line:90%
into that 20-minute lecture.

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:57.300 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:58.480 align:middle line:90%
So set it up.

00:19:58.480 --> 00:19:59.280 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yes.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:02.250 align:middle line:84%
So there are some
kids that seem to have

00:20:02.250 --> 00:20:06.180 align:middle line:84%
a preternatural
intelligence or ability.

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:09.270 align:middle line:84%
It's most closely associated
with child prodigies.

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:10.410 align:middle line:90%
He stunned his father.

00:20:10.410 --> 00:20:11.970 align:middle line:84%
His father was
teaching, I think,

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:13.740 align:middle line:84%
a college course
and was preparing

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:15.480 align:middle line:90%
to go off to work that morning.

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:18.540 align:middle line:84%
And his son sort of
lectured him and used

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:21.450 align:middle line:84%
words that were just
not in the vocabulary

00:20:21.450 --> 00:20:22.630 align:middle line:90%
of a typical five-year-old.

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:24.900 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well about the
subject of God and man.

00:20:24.900 --> 00:20:26.970 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Yes, very
profound subjects.

00:20:26.970 --> 00:20:32.040 align:middle line:10%
And he was expounding about
God, and truth, and the word

00:20:32.040 --> 00:20:33.390 align:middle line:10%
of being, and so forth.

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:35.670 align:middle line:84%
And his father
didn't understand it.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:40.230 align:middle line:84%
But I think he says in the
book that just this realization

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:43.260 align:middle line:84%
dawned on him that something
amazing was happening.

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:46.920 align:middle line:84%
Kind of a feeling right
up his spine like this

00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:47.825 align:middle line:90%
is just not ordinary.

00:20:47.825 --> 00:20:48.700 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Not normal.

00:20:48.700 --> 00:20:49.500 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:20:49.500 --> 00:20:51.540 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Yeah, yeah,
but it is very human.

00:20:51.540 --> 00:20:53.530 align:middle line:84%
And the question is,
where does it come from?

00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:54.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well that's
the interesting part.

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:56.553 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot of
conjecture around that.

00:20:56.553 --> 00:20:58.200 align:middle line:84%
One of the things
you said in the book

00:20:58.200 --> 00:21:00.450 align:middle line:84%
is that the son's
eyes appeared--

00:21:00.450 --> 00:21:02.700 align:middle line:84%
he was in a very monotone
voice, and his eyes

00:21:02.700 --> 00:21:05.700 align:middle line:84%
appeared to just be very
still, almost glossed over

00:21:05.700 --> 00:21:08.010 align:middle line:84%
as he was allowing
this information

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:09.030 align:middle line:90%
to flow through him.

00:21:09.030 --> 00:21:13.410 align:middle line:84%
Now if you turn to metaphysical
or you turn to religious sects,

00:21:13.410 --> 00:21:15.720 align:middle line:84%
they're going to say,
well, someone was speaking

00:21:15.720 --> 00:21:17.670 align:middle line:90%
through him, not of him.

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:19.110 align:middle line:84%
So how would you
respond to that?

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:20.818 align:middle line:84%
Because with our
audience a lot of people

00:21:20.818 --> 00:21:22.783 align:middle line:84%
are going to say the guy
was channeling, right?

00:21:22.783 --> 00:21:23.700 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Right, right.

00:21:23.700 --> 00:21:26.880 align:middle line:84%
And I'd bring up the
term dissociation again.

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:29.070 align:middle line:84%
Because whenever somebody
is sort of distant

00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:30.415 align:middle line:90%
from themselves, which--

00:21:30.415 --> 00:21:32.040 align:middle line:84%
you mentioned trauma
before, that's why

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:34.410 align:middle line:84%
I said dissociation is
part and parcel of trauma,

00:21:34.410 --> 00:21:36.150 align:middle line:84%
people lose their
sense of themselves.

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:40.230 align:middle line:84%
And they don't feel things
as they typically do.

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:43.680 align:middle line:84%
And in all cases where
you have mediums--

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:46.162 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, can
that leave them open?

00:21:46.162 --> 00:21:48.630 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: They are dissociating
from their own day-to-day

00:21:48.630 --> 00:21:49.230 align:middle line:90%
experience.

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:50.940 align:middle line:84%
And the question is
what are they accessing?

00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:51.810 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What are
they accessing?

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:52.620 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:21:52.620 --> 00:21:55.170 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: And it's hard to say
because, Regina, certainly

00:21:55.170 --> 00:21:59.640 align:middle line:84%
there are authors of
terrific works of fiction

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:03.060 align:middle line:84%
who develop so many different
kinds of characters.

00:22:03.060 --> 00:22:05.445 align:middle line:84%
And they will say that when
they sit down to write--

00:22:05.445 --> 00:22:06.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It just shows up.

00:22:06.570 --> 00:22:07.350 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: --it just shows up.

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And they don't know
how they're coming up

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.800 align:middle line:84%
with this incredible
creativity, but they come up

00:22:11.800 --> 00:22:13.050 align:middle line:90%
with very distinct characters.

00:22:13.050 --> 00:22:14.310 align:middle line:84%
And they don't know
where the story is going.

00:22:14.310 --> 00:22:16.750 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's like they're
literally just transcribing

00:22:16.750 --> 00:22:17.610 align:middle line:90%
something.

00:22:17.610 --> 00:22:19.620 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: They feel that
the muse is guiding them

00:22:19.620 --> 00:22:21.360 align:middle line:90%
and they are just the vessel.

00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:22.818 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I mean
with someone who's

00:22:22.818 --> 00:22:25.410 align:middle line:84%
five to give a 20-minute
discourse on the nature of God

00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:27.600 align:middle line:84%
and man, it would
certainly seem it's not

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:30.570 align:middle line:84%
coming from his personal
experience at this point.

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:32.710 align:middle line:84%
It is coming from
something somewhere.

00:22:32.710 --> 00:22:33.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:33.510 --> 00:22:34.310 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Yeah.

00:22:34.310 --> 00:22:35.880 align:middle line:84%
And what I look
at in the book is

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:39.930 align:middle line:84%
the process of possible prenatal
precursor to what's happening.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:42.480 align:middle line:84%
Because what I
sort of alighted on

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:46.380 align:middle line:84%
is that in many cases
of child prodigies,

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.510 align:middle line:84%
and they display these
kinds of uncanny abilities.

00:22:51.510 --> 00:22:53.580 align:middle line:84%
And recollections,
they have recollections

00:22:53.580 --> 00:22:55.350 align:middle line:90%
of being in utero.

00:22:55.350 --> 00:22:59.040 align:middle line:84%
And they have,
apparently, recollections

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:01.390 align:middle line:84%
of somebody else's
life in some cases.

00:23:01.390 --> 00:23:03.030 align:middle line:90%
So where does that come from?

00:23:03.030 --> 00:23:05.950 align:middle line:84%
What I noticed is that
in many of these cases,

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:09.420 align:middle line:84%
there was some issue
during the pregnancy.

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:13.230 align:middle line:84%
In some cases, the mother
suffered a severe shock.

00:23:13.230 --> 00:23:14.672 align:middle line:90%
There was an accident.

00:23:14.672 --> 00:23:16.380 align:middle line:84%
In one case that's
mentioned in the book,

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:20.010 align:middle line:84%
the husband and wife came
home when she was pregnant

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:22.650 align:middle line:84%
and they found people that were
breaking into their home, which

00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:24.540 align:middle line:90%
was scary.

00:23:24.540 --> 00:23:26.940 align:middle line:84%
There's also conditions
like preeclampsia,

00:23:26.940 --> 00:23:28.620 align:middle line:84%
which is apparently
something that can

00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:31.950 align:middle line:90%
affect the pregnancy adversely.

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:34.602 align:middle line:84%
And premature births as
well and difficult births.

00:23:34.602 --> 00:23:36.810 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So let's say you've
had a challenging birth

00:23:36.810 --> 00:23:38.850 align:middle line:84%
or you've had a
challenging gestation,

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:40.880 align:middle line:84%
so what are you saying
this does to the being?

00:23:40.880 --> 00:23:44.220 align:middle line:84%
It creates more of a
dissociative pattern

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:47.340 align:middle line:84%
or potential in them
that can essentially

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:49.830 align:middle line:84%
allow for something
else to come in

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:52.042 align:middle line:84%
and kind of claim that
space energetically?

00:23:52.042 --> 00:23:53.250 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: Something like that.

00:23:53.250 --> 00:23:56.070 align:middle line:84%
My guesstimate about this--
and it's sheer speculation--

00:23:56.070 --> 00:23:59.940 align:middle line:84%
but my guesstimate
is that there may be

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:01.620 align:middle line:90%
something preceding this life.

00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:02.790 align:middle line:90%
Who knows what that is.

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:06.520 align:middle line:84%
These kids, I believe, have
a closer connection to that

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:10.000 align:middle line:84%
because the fact that
their gestation was not

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.670 align:middle line:84%
the typical pattern, that there
was something that happened.

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:13.930 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They were shaken
out of their comfort.

00:24:13.930 --> 00:24:15.130 align:middle line:90%
>>JAWER: They were.

00:24:15.130 --> 00:24:18.970 align:middle line:84%
Something got shaken up and so
there's an echo, so to speak,

00:24:18.970 --> 00:24:22.840 align:middle line:84%
of what came before, that
there are traces of that.

00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:24.700 align:middle line:84%
And they generally
lose those traces

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:26.518 align:middle line:90%
by about age six or seven.

00:24:26.518 --> 00:24:28.810 align:middle line:84%
But they're very evident in
some kids up to that point.

00:24:28.810 --> 00:24:29.685 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right, yes.

00:24:29.685 --> 00:24:32.830 align:middle line:84%
I mean reading
Carol Bowman's book,

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:34.900 align:middle line:84%
you know Ian Stevenson's
research and all that

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:37.280 align:middle line:84%
on children and past
lives-- and we're

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:39.030 align:middle line:84%
going to get to something
in a moment that

00:24:39.030 --> 00:24:41.140 align:middle line:90%
could sound like that.

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:43.603 align:middle line:84%
One thing you wrote
about is a lot of times--

00:24:43.603 --> 00:24:45.520 align:middle line:84%
and forgive me if I can't
remember if it was--

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:49.220 align:middle line:84%
whether it was prodigies or
children with autism often

00:24:49.220 --> 00:24:50.020 align:middle line:90%
have--

00:24:50.020 --> 00:24:52.630 align:middle line:84%
I think it was prodigies
have a very difficult time

00:24:52.630 --> 00:24:55.370 align:middle line:90%
with injustice.

00:24:55.370 --> 00:24:57.468 align:middle line:84%
They're very sensitive
to injustice.

00:24:57.468 --> 00:24:59.260 align:middle line:84%
Talk about that for
just a second before we

00:24:59.260 --> 00:25:01.210 align:middle line:84%
go into some of
these other stories.

00:25:01.210 --> 00:25:04.110 align:middle line:84%
>>JAWER: Well one example might
